---
import BaseLayout from '../components/layout/BaseLayout.astro';
import { SITE } from '../config/site';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About"
  description="About Asavin Wattanajantra and Editorial Intelligence OS."
>
  <div class="container-site py-20">
    <div class="max-w-2xl">
      <header class="mb-16">
        <p class="t-label mb-6">About</p>
        <h1 class="t-heading mb-6">{SITE.author}</h1>
        <p class="text-lg text-[var(--color-ink-secondary)] leading-relaxed">
          {SITE.title}
        </p>
      </header>

      <hr class="divider mb-16" />

      <div class="about-photo mb-16">
        <img src="/Images/asavin.jpg" alt="Asavin Wattanajantra" class="about-img" />
      </div>

      <div class="about-prose">
        <p>
          I'm an Editorial Intelligence practitioner — working at the intersection of research, narrative and knowledge systems to help organisations turn what they already know into connected positions that compound over time.
        </p>
        <p>
          The ideas on this site emerged from practical work — most extensively at Sage, where programmes like <a href="/narratives/hidden-hours" class="text-[var(--color-accent)] no-underline hover:underline">Hidden Hours</a>, <a href="/narratives/winning-in-small" class="text-[var(--color-accent)] no-underline hover:underline">Winning in Small</a> and <a href="/narratives/trusted-ai" class="text-[var(--color-accent)] no-underline hover:underline">Trusted AI</a> developed into something beyond content campaigns: knowledge systems designed to strengthen with every new cycle of evidence.
        </p>

        <h2>Where this came from</h2>
        <p>
          This isn't theory. It's two decades of content practice, synthesised.
        </p>
        <p>
          I started in journalism. Then editorial roles in publishing. Then content strategy, thought leadership, research programmes — building campaigns, commissioning work, running evidence-based content at scale. For most of that time I was operating with an instinct I couldn't fully articulate: that the most valuable thing you could do with a piece of research wasn't publish it, but connect it. Let it pull in the next thing. Build on it rather than starting over.
        </p>
        <p>
          That instinct ran through everything: the way a good research programme can sustain three years of thought leadership if you treat it as an evidence base rather than a report. The way customer stories stop being testimonials and start being intelligence when you look for patterns across them. The way webinar and event conversations generate sharper signals than most surveys — if someone captures them properly.
        </p>
        <p>
          AI changed what was possible. Not the thinking — the thinking was already there — but the speed at which accumulated knowledge could be structured, externalised and made navigable. The arrival of AI made synthesis more valuable, not less. It accelerated the collection of evidence. It did nothing to improve its interpretation.
        </p>
        <p>
          That gap — between evidence collected and evidence understood — became the discipline I'd been practising without naming it.
        </p>
        <p style="font-style: italic; color: var(--color-ink-tertiary); border-left: 2px solid var(--color-accent); padding-left: 1.25rem;">
          Editorial Intelligence.
        </p>

        <h2>The discipline, the OS, the consulting</h2>
        <p>
          Editorial Intelligence is the discipline — the principles for how organisations turn distributed evidence into better decisions, stronger narratives and reusable knowledge.
        </p>
        <p>
          <a href="/editorial-intelligence-os" class="text-[var(--color-accent)] no-underline hover:underline">Editorial Intelligence OS</a> is the practical operating system built from that discipline — the frameworks, methods, assessments, AI workflows and guides that make it repeatable.
        </p>
        <p>
          My <a href="/work" class="text-[var(--color-accent)] no-underline hover:underline">consulting</a> is implementation — helping organisations build the editorial capability, narrative systems and evidence infrastructure to make the discipline work in their specific context.
        </p>
        <p>
          This site documents all three: the discipline developing in public, the OS being built iteratively, and the consulting work that keeps both grounded in practical reality.
        </p>

        <h2>Writing portfolio</h2>
        <p>
          My published work — articles, research narratives and editorial projects — is collected on Authory.
        </p>
        <p>
          <a href="https://authory.com/asavin" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-[var(--color-accent)] no-underline hover:underline">
            authory.com/asavin
          </a>
        </p>

        <h2>Get in touch</h2>
        <p>
          If you're working on similar problems — connecting organisational knowledge, building editorial systems, or thinking about AI and strategic content — I'd like to hear from you.
        </p>

        <div class="contact-links">
          <a href="mailto:asavin@editorialintelligence.co" class="contact-link">
            <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
              <rect x="1" y="3" width="14" height="10" rx="1.5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.25"/>
              <path d="M1 5l7 5 7-5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.25" stroke-linecap="round"/>
            </svg>
            asavin@editorialintelligence.co
          </a>
          <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/ashwat/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="contact-link">
            <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
              <rect x="1" y="1" width="14" height="14" rx="2" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.25"/>
              <path d="M4 6.5v5M4 4v.5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.25" stroke-linecap="round"/>
              <path d="M7.5 11.5V9a2 2 0 014 0v2.5M7.5 6.5v5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.25" stroke-linecap="round"/>
            </svg>
            linkedin.com/in/ashwat
          </a>
          <a href="https://authory.com/asavin" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="contact-link">
            <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
              <path d="M3 4h10M3 8h7M3 12h5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.25" stroke-linecap="round"/>
            </svg>
            authory.com/asavin
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <hr class="divider mt-16 mb-10" />

      <a href="/start" style="display:inline-flex;align-items:center;gap:0.375rem;font-family:var(--font-mono);font-size:0.8125rem;color:var(--color-accent);text-decoration:none;">
        New to Editorial Intelligence? Start here →
      </a>

    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .about-prose p,
  .about-prose h2 {
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }

  .about-prose p {
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.8;
    color: var(--color-ink-secondary);
  }

  .about-prose h2 {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: 1.375rem;
    font-weight: 400;
    color: var(--color-ink);
    margin-top: 2.5rem;
    letter-spacing: -0.01em;
  }

  .contact-links {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    margin-top: 1.25rem;
  }

  .contact-link {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.625rem;
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.8125rem;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    text-decoration: none;
    transition: opacity 0.15s;
  }

  .contact-link:hover {
    opacity: 0.75;
  }

  .contact-link svg {
    color: var(--color-ink-tertiary);
    flex-shrink: 0;
  }

  .about-photo {
    border-radius: 6px;
    overflow: hidden;
  }

  .about-img {
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 480px;
    height: auto;
    display: block;
    border-radius: 6px;
    object-fit: cover;
  }
</style>
